[![Open in Gitpod](https://gitpod.io/button/open-in-gitpod.svg)](https://gitpod.io/from-referrer/)

These lemmas come from my work on trying to prove that if we write something to the memory and the address remains untouched by further writing, we can later read it. The memory is built upon a `byteArray`, and a key operation, 'copyslice,' is defined based on 'extract'.

nodes.body: @semorrison This is the initial commit of the Array extract part (with two lemma about get).
I'm not going to have time to review this. But please label as `awaiting-review` when you are ready for someone to have a look.

@semorrison  I have rewritten the proof to make it clearer, shorter and more dependent on existing theorems. Additionally, regarding your suggestion to move this to std or lean, I think std might be a better choice because it utilizes lemmas from the library.
Title of PR should be `feat: lemmas about Array.extract`.

@semorrison, I have simplified the proof based on your suggestion. Please review it again. Omega is very useful. :) By the way, I feel it is not necessary to open a new file since the proof is now very short. However, since you mentioned that you want to deliver it into std., I have not changed the file structure for now.
Separately, would you mind clicking "resolve" on conversations above where you've already responded? It helps when another reviewer arrives.

After making these last changes, you can then merge it yourself:

bors d+

:v: JiechengZhao can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
Thanks for the contribution, and your patience through the review! :-)
